age_repeat="no-repeat" rt_bg_size="cover" rt_bg_position="right top" rt_bg_attachment="fixed" rt_row_borders="top,bottom" rt_grid="" rt_padding_top="60" rt_padding_bottom="60"][vc_column width="1/1"][rt_heading style="style-4" size="h4"]Our Story[/rt_heading][rt_timeline id=""][rt_tl_event month="December," year="2012"]<span style="font-weight: 400;">After attending SOAS together (from 2005-2006) and maintaining a strong connection for six years, Hart and Daniel convene at Cafe Nero, Regent Street, London. Hart had already been admitted to the Nigerian bar in 2008. They discuss Hart’s involvement in the firm. Hart goes home to pray on the decision, and then confirms interest weeks later.</span>[/rt_tl_event][rt_tl_event year="2013/2014"]<span style="font-weight: 400;">Collectively, we refined our firm’s strategy and value proposition, having mapped our business opportunities and competitive advantages. Our structural and operational foundations were in place by Q4 of 2014.  Accordingly, we embarked on the processes to formally incorporate the firm under section 659 of the Nigerian Companies and Allied Matters Act (1990).</span>[/rt_tl_event][rt_tl_event month="March," year="2015"]<span style="font-weight: 400;">The Corporate Affairs Commission (CAC) of Nigeria incorporates the firm as a legal entity. DanielHart &amp; Dayo LLP is listed in the CAC’s register of business names, and certified as a “legal practice and consultancy” with the following certification number: BN2337967.</span>[/rt_tl_event][rt_tl_event month="March," year="2015"]<span style="font-weight: 400;">Client enquires are being answered.</span>[/rt_tl_event][/rt_timeline][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row rt_row_background_width="default" rt_row_content_width="default" rt_row_style="alt-style-2" rt_row_paddings="true" rt_bg_effect="classic" rt_bg_parallax_effect="1" rt_bg_image_repeat="repeat" rt_bg_size="cover" rt_bg_position="right top" rt_bg_attachment="scroll" rt_overlap="" rt_padding_top="60" rt_padding_bottom="60" rt_row_borders="" rt_grid=""][vc_column width="1/1"][rt_heading size="h3" style="style-4" punchline="Testimonials"]What They Are Saying[/rt_heading][testimonial_carousel list_layout="1/1" align="center" max_item="10" nav="false" dots="true" list_orderby="date" list_order="DESC" client_images="false" style="center big" ids="2353,1735"][/vc_column][/vc_row]', 'ABOUT US', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '9-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-11-05 12:45:43', '2015-11-05 12:45:43', '', 9, 'http://www.danielhartdayo.com/2015/11/05/9-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(3027, 1, '2015-11-05 12:47:34', '2015-11-05 12:47:34', '<strong><span class="cinzel" style="font-size: 25px;">Daniel Akinmade Emejulu</span></strong>\r\n<strong><span class="cinzel" style="font-size: 25px;">Managing Partner</span></strong>\r\n\r\nDaniel is the multi-stakeholder specialist. He advises clients on their corporate citizenship in Nigeria. Daniel provides strategies to build each client’s responsible business partnerships in Nigeria—with agents of government, business and civil society. His insights on corporate citizenship and the multi-stakeholder approach have been polished at the world’s foremost institution for public-private collaboration: The World Economic Forum. He also gained cross-sector experiences in settings such as the United Nations Office in Vienna, the Red Cross in Nigeria, Simmons &amp; Simmons in London, and government ministries in both Nigeria and the UK. In 2014, Daniel led a WEF publication for global executives to catalyze private sector involvement in the Ebola response effort, which featured interviews with the Presidents of Liberia, Sierra Leone, Mali and Paul G. Allen who had donated $100million to the response effort.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="font-weight: bold;">Professional experience</span>\r\n- World Economic Forum, Geneva, Switzerland, 2013 –\r\n- Law Office of David Umar (Nigerian Senator from Niger State), Abuja, Nigeria, 2011\r\n- Simmons &amp; Simmons LLP, London, United Kingdom, 2008\r\n\r\n<b>Professional qualification</b>\r\nAdmitted as Barrister and Solicitor, Supreme Court of Nigeria, 2012 (February)\r\n\r\n<b>Academic qualifications</b>\r\n- BL, Barrister-at-Law, The Nigerian Law School, Abuja, Nigeria, 2010 – 2011\r\n- LLM, Master of Laws, Duke University, NC, United States of America, 2008 – 2009\r\n- LLB, Bachelor of Laws, SOAS, University of London, United Kingdom, 2005 – 2008\r\n\r\n<b>Trivia</b>\r\nIn the firm, Daniel acts as Managing Partner with responsibility for overall coordination of the firm. He also leads our efforts to build relationships with prospective clients outside of Nigeria, and created the Millennial Lawyers Club.\r\n\r\nOutside of the firm, Daniel enjoys writing stories, occasional acting and amateur skiing. D’Banj, Lagbaja, Asa and Wizkid are his favorite living Nigerian musicians.\r\n\r\n<b>Languages</b>\r\nEnglish (Mother tongue) French (Conversational) Yoruba (Basic)', 'Daniel Akinmade Emejulu', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1872-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-11-05 12:47:34', '2015-11-05 12:47:34', '', 1872, 'http://www.danielhartdayo.com/2015/11/05/1872-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
